You try here in fact to convert an instance of a base class to an instance of a derived class.


You are not allowed to write:

&gt;     A a = new A();

&gt;     B b = (B)a;

When:

&gt;     public class A { }

&gt;     public class B : A { }

Because if B is type of A, A is not type of B.

`B` is a **specialization** of `A` : `B` is an *enlarged* `A` so `B` &quot;fits&quot; in `A`.

`A` is a **generalization** of `B` : `A` is a *reduced* `B` so `A` &quot;does not fit&quot; in `B`.

To understand think about aging : when you are young you know little things and when you are old you know more things, so you young do not fit in you old while you old fit in you young, as when young your are not yet you old but when you are old you stay you.

